23
00:01:12.276 --> 00:01:15.086
and the jargon that they've 
already inputted into the AI system 

24
00:01:15.086 --> 00:01:17.890
so that they can 
have an easier time 

25
00:01:17.890 --> 00:01:19.890
of translating us today.

26
00:01:21.920 --> 00:01:26.968
We're going to look at 
"to caption or not to caption" 

27
00:01:26.968 --> 00:01:30.964
but in my view, actually, 
there is really no question. 

28
00:01:30.964 --> 00:01:33.264
We need to be doing this. 

29
00:01:33.264 --> 00:01:38.749
I'm not going to be focusing 
on the how but more on the why. 

30
00:01:38.749 --> 00:01:42.623
Why are we talking 
about subtitling today? 

31
00:01:42.623 --> 00:01:47.939
Well, simply, you do not have 
a finished video product 

32
00:01:47.939 --> 00:01:50.681
unless you have subtitles. 

33
00:01:50.681 --> 00:01:53.026
Hopefully through this presentation, 

34
00:01:53.026 --> 00:01:55.680
you'll see why that is so important.

35
00:02:00.080 --> 00:02:03.333
Streaming video has 
increasingly accounted 

36
00:02:03.333 --> 00:02:06.320
for a large proportion 
of all internet usage.

37
00:02:06.320 --> 00:02:09.000
The most recent 
survey by Statista, 

38
00:02:09.000 --> 00:02:11.000
a company which 
researches key aspects 

39
00:02:11.000 --> 00:02:13.000
of business data worldwide, 

40
00:02:13.000 --> 00:02:18.416
found that video represented 
up to 95% of all internet usage 

41
00:02:18.416 --> 00:02:21.520
in some of the countries they sampled. 

42
00:02:21.520 --> 00:02:23.969
Research since continues to show 

43
00:02:23.969 --> 00:02:26.000
that in most countries the trend 

44
00:02:26.000 --> 00:02:28.249
for online streaming of video 

45
00:02:28.249 --> 00:02:31.280
has had a big growth trajectory. 

46
00:02:31.280 --> 00:02:36.240
During the pandemic, 
not surprisingly, it has soared.

47
00:02:36.240 --> 00:02:38.430
The effects of the COVID situation 

48
00:02:38.430 --> 00:02:41.840
have resulted in a 
further explosion of demand

49
00:02:41.840 --> 00:02:46.693
for online streaming access 
from businesses, social organizations, 

50
00:02:46.693 --> 00:02:51.280
special interest groups, 
and private individuals across the world. 

51
00:02:51.280 --> 00:02:55.440
Online video consumption 
really cannot be ignored

52
00:02:56.000 --> 00:02:59.000
by businesses or 
other organizations. 

53
00:02:59.000 --> 00:03:02.400
It needs to be part of 
your marketing strategy,

54
00:03:02.400 --> 00:03:05.392
your engagement, 
your knowledge management, 

55
00:03:05.392 --> 00:03:07.392
and ultimately your sales.

56
00:03:08.640 --> 00:03:11.649
In [an] increasingly crowded marketplace 

57
00:03:11.649 --> 00:03:15.360
with more sophisticated 
production software now available,

58
00:03:15.360 --> 00:03:18.360
it makes no sense 
to omit that final part 

59
00:03:18.360 --> 00:03:21.360
of what should be 
in all of our checklists,

60
00:03:21.360 --> 00:03:25.340
and I hope after today you will 
have this in your checklist: 

61
00:03:25.340 --> 00:03:27.880
subtitling and captions.

62
00:03:30.000 --> 00:03:33.280
First, let's have a look at 
what these things really are.

63
00:03:34.160 --> 00:03:37.660
That is, of course, 
from being life-changing 

64
00:03:37.660 --> 00:03:40.929
for some of our colleagues, 
vital learning tools, 

65
00:03:40.929 --> 00:03:45.840
and increasingly essential 
for search engines.

66
00:03:49.600 --> 00:03:52.981
Basically, if you don't 
have that subtitle 

67
00:03:52.981 --> 00:03:55.440
this is what is going to happen:

68
00:03:57.360 --> 00:04:02.022
People won't be able to access it 
in a variety of mediums, 

69
00:04:02.022 --> 00:04:04.683
and search engines certainly can't. 

70
00:04:04.683 --> 00:04:06.800
We'll be talking more about that 
through this presentation.

71
00:04:08.400 --> 00:04:13.065
Now, we often come across 
two terms of subtitles and captions 

72
00:04:13.065 --> 00:04:15.360
as if they mean the same thing.

73
00:04:16.640 --> 00:04:19.000
But there are actually three terms 

74
00:04:19.000 --> 00:04:21.200
that are widely used 
in the media production.

75
00:04:25.040 --> 00:04:27.670
Subtitles, open captions, 
and closed captions 

76
00:04:27.670 --> 00:04:29.750
as you can see on the screen. 

77
00:04:29.750 --> 00:04:31.750
That's what the technical definition is. 

78
00:04:31.750 --> 00:04:35.151
They do not actually 
mean the same thing. 

79
00:04:35.151 --> 00:04:38.000
At the moment there are 
three main types.

80
00:04:39.680 --> 00:04:43.125
We'll come to images and 
the new type of captioning 

81
00:04:43.125 --> 00:04:44.880
that is coming in later on.

82
00:04:45.920 --> 00:04:52.471
Fundamentally, they all mean 
a visual on-screen text representation 

83
00:04:51.471 --> 00:04:56.893
of the words heard in an audio track, 
or a video, or your broadcast. 

84
00:04:56.893 --> 00:05:01.104
You'll often hear these 
terms interchangeably, 

85
00:05:01.104 --> 00:05:03.764
but you do need to know 
which of the terms 

86
00:05:03.764 --> 00:05:07.216
you actually need for your 
product and your organization, 

87
00:05:07.216 --> 00:05:10.501
depending on the environment, 
and the ecosystem,

88
00:05:10.501 --> 00:05:12.640
the regulatory framework 
that you're operating in.

89
00:05:14.720 --> 00:05:18.373
Captions come in two varieties: 
open or closed. 

90
00:05:18.373 --> 00:05:21.280
Both go further than 
simple subtitling.

91
00:05:22.080 --> 00:05:25.275
They not only represent 
the spoken words. 

92
00:05:25.275 --> 00:05:29.840
They include text descriptions 
of all non-verbal sounds

93
00:05:29.840 --> 00:05:32.905
which may form 
part of that presentation. 

94
00:05:32.905 --> 00:05:36.480
Captions amplify the dialogue, 
the narrative,

95
00:05:36.480 --> 00:05:39.295
with descriptions of sounds 
that would be included 

96
00:05:39.295 --> 00:05:41.840
through the subtitling 
of that spoken language.

97
00:05:42.400 --> 00:05:48.880
For example: woman coughs loudly;
sound of breaking glass; dog barks.

98
00:05:49.520 --> 00:05:54.831
(I always wait for my dog 
to actually see that as a command.); 

99
00:05:54.831 --> 00:05:57.238
doorbell rings; music plays. 

100
00:05:57.238 --> 00:06:00.239
This is to try and get as closely 

101
00:06:00.239 --> 00:06:03.902
to the atmosphere and feel 
of the audio track. 

102
00:06:03.902 --> 00:06:06.838
It's much more interesting 
for the person 

103
00:06:06.838 --> 00:06:09.638
who can't access 
the words or the sound, 

104
00:06:09.638 --> 00:06:13.920
to have a better idea 
of what is being represented.

105
00:06:16.000 --> 00:06:19.250
Providing captions can 
have a greater implication 

106
00:06:19.250 --> 00:06:22.827
on production time 
and costs of subtitling. 

107
00:06:22.827 --> 00:06:27.120
But both continue to become 
easier to create and synchronize

108
00:06:27.120 --> 00:06:29.588
through the development 
of enabling software 

109
00:06:29.588 --> 00:06:31.144
and artificial intelligence. 

110
00:06:31.144 --> 00:06:33.685
As a firm, we do a lot 
of work in this area.

111
00:06:33.685 --> 00:06:37.960
It's so wonderful to see it 
becoming more accessible.

112
00:06:38.720 --> 00:06:40.645
I've mentioned two forms of captions. 

113
00:06:40.645 --> 00:06:43.177
Open captions are captions 
embedded in the video 

114
00:06:43.177 --> 00:06:46.675
at production stage, 
and are on screen permanently. 

115
00:06:46.675 --> 00:06:50.240
The viewer cannot choose 
whether they appear or not.

116
00:06:51.200 --> 00:06:54.760
I've kept this slide up, because when 
I've done this presentation before, 

117
00:06:54.760 --> 00:06:57.927
people have said they felt 
it was easier for them 

118
00:06:57.927 --> 00:07:01.461
to understand the difference 
when we have this up. 

119
00:07:01.461 --> 00:07:06.004
Closed captions are interactive 
in what they can be 

120
00:07:06.004 --> 00:07:09.971
turned off or on or off 
at the choice of the viewer. 

121
00:07:09.971 --> 00:07:11.619
A quick toggle 
of the remote control 

122
00:07:11.619 --> 00:07:14.823
and, hey, presto - 
captions on, captions off. 

123
00:07:14.823 --> 00:07:19.161
A bit like the mute button 
for audio volume. 

124
00:07:19.161 --> 00:07:21.293
Captions can be 
a legal requirement 

125
00:07:21.293 --> 00:07:23.726
in some jurisdictions 
for videos intended 

126
00:07:23.726 --> 00:07:26.253
to be broadcast in public, 

127
00:07:26.253 --> 00:07:27.858
and they're enforced through 

128
00:07:27.858 --> 00:07:29.892
the various countries' legal systems. 

129
00:07:29.892 --> 00:07:31.244
As ever, I would urge you 

130
00:07:31.244 --> 00:07:34.000
to look at the regulations 
in your own jurisdiction.

131
00:07:34.560 --> 00:07:37.172
You may find these 
in a variety of places –

132
00:07:37.172 --> 00:07:40.828
from broadcasting legislation, 
equality, 

133
00:07:40.828 --> 00:07:44.698
anti-discrimination regulations, 
to communications and media laws 

134
00:07:44.698 --> 00:07:49.360
– but also in the ethos and values 
of your own organization. 

135
00:07:49.360 --> 00:07:51.840
The penalties for infringement 
can be high,

136
00:07:52.640 --> 00:07:57.800
and it's worth including 
the captions and subtitles 

137
00:07:57.800 --> 00:08:00.000
in your initial brief, 
in your scoping.

138
00:08:02.720 --> 00:08:05.572
In some locations, 
the requirements apply 

139
00:08:05.572 --> 00:08:08.042
to both public bodies 
and organizations 

140
00:08:08.042 --> 00:08:10.500
with registered charitable status, 

141
00:08:10.500 --> 00:08:12.000
so do your homework. 

142
00:08:12.000 --> 00:08:14.000
Check what it is that you need.

143
00:08:15.680 --> 00:08:19.874
Apart from legal compliance 
where it applies, 

144
00:08:19.874 --> 00:08:24.500
why should we provide 
subtitles and captions? 

145
00:08:24.828 --> 00:08:29.632
Subtitling is a way to make that 
video material more accessible. 

146
00:08:29.632 --> 00:08:33.413
It actually makes it possible 
for someone with a hearing difficulty 

147
00:08:33.413 --> 00:08:36.657
to hear the message 
behind the video at all.

148
00:08:37.520 --> 00:08:42.129
But there are a lot of 
myths about subtitling 

149
00:08:42.129 --> 00:08:44.338
and why you shouldn't do it. 

150
00:08:44.338 --> 00:08:47.500
Hopefully today we'll debunk 
some of those myths. 

151
00:08:48.589 --> 00:08:52.497
Hearing disabilities can be caused 
by a large variety of reasons, 

152
00:08:52.497 --> 00:08:56.492
from disabilities from birth, 
trauma, injury related, 

153
00:08:56.492 --> 00:08:59.303
and from actually just getting older, 

154
00:08:59.303 --> 00:09:01.921
as well as health-related issues. 

155
00:09:01.921 --> 00:09:04.216
They may be temporary, 
they may be permanent. 

156
00:09:04.216 --> 00:09:07.289
We have a number of 
colleagues in my work 

157
00:09:07.289 --> 00:09:09.599
and in the WordPress community 

158
00:09:09.599 --> 00:09:12.630
who have some kind 
of hearing impairment. 

159
00:09:13.482 --> 00:09:15.229
In our work, 
in both of these areas, 

160
00:09:15.229 --> 00:09:16.900
we've been running 
awareness surveys 

161
00:09:16.900 --> 00:09:20.989
around what people 
think subtitles are for. 

162
00:09:20.989 --> 00:09:24.242
Our panel found that there 
were myths about subtitling 

163
00:09:24.242 --> 00:09:28.000
that continue to exist, 
and continue to be shared.

164
00:09:29.840 --> 00:09:32.500
People think that it's outdated.

165
00:09:34.320 --> 00:09:37.952
They think that when 
someone appears on a video, 

166
00:09:37.952 --> 00:09:40.640
words pop up 
automatically underneath

167
00:09:40.640 --> 00:09:43.825
as soon as someone 
clicks a button. 

168
00:09:44.575 --> 00:09:47.257
They thought that 
subtitling is there 

169
00:09:47.257 --> 00:09:51.077
for people who do not have 
a computer with sound. 

170
00:09:51.077 --> 00:09:54.560
You will be surprised how often 
that comes up as a reason!

171
00:09:56.800 --> 00:10:01.250
People also think that accessibility 
does not relate to video.

172
00:10:02.640 --> 00:10:05.246
The one that we increasingly hear: 

173
00:10:05.246 --> 00:10:06.766
it's for old people, 

174
00:10:06.766 --> 00:10:09.992
or for people who really 
aren't our customers.

175
00:10:09.992 --> 00:10:12.680
Therefore we don't need 
to worry about it.

176
00:10:15.040 --> 00:10:19.277
The American National 
Association of the Deaf estimate – 

177
00:10:19.277 --> 00:10:22.913
I'm waiting for my slides 
to catch up on your screens.

178
00:10:22.913 --> 00:10:26.880
I'm hoping that they have.

179
00:10:29.000 --> 00:10:33.000
Hopefully you've got a screen 
that shows a blue screen and orange, 

180
00:10:33.000 --> 00:10:35.414
but if not I'll talk over it. 

181
00:10:35.414 --> 00:10:38.329
The American National 
Association of the Deaf estimates 

182
00:10:38.329 --> 00:10:41.351
that five to six percent 
of the global population 

183
00:10:41.351 --> 00:10:43.588
has some form 
of hearing impairment. 

184
00:10:44.288 --> 00:10:46.285
That, at the time 
of their investigation, 

185
00:10:46.285 --> 00:10:51.156
translates to around 
350 million people who, 

186
00:10:51.156 --> 00:10:54.400
assuming they have 
access to technology

187
00:10:54.400 --> 00:10:57.455
in order to watch streamed video, 

188
00:10:57.455 --> 00:11:00.840
would be able to benefit 
from subtitling or captioning.

189
00:11:01.600 --> 00:11:03.460
Even allowing for a proportion 

190
00:11:03.460 --> 00:11:06.640
of those not having the 
means to access the internet

191
00:11:07.200 --> 00:11:11.821
there is still a massive 
potential audience to cater for. 

192
00:11:11.821 --> 00:11:14.640
On the 1st of March 
of this year, 2020,

193
00:11:14.640 --> 00:11:18.207
the World Health Organization estimated 

194
00:11:18.207 --> 00:11:22.153
that 466 million people 

195
00:11:22.153 --> 00:11:25.560
have had a disabling hearing loss.

196
00:11:25.840 --> 00:11:32.734
It predicted the figure rising 
to 900 million by 2050 – 

197
00:11:32.734 --> 00:11:36.757
to 900 million by 2050,
unless concerted action 

198
00:11:36.757 --> 00:11:41.282
to address some of the 
preventable causes was taken. 

199
00:11:41.282 --> 00:11:45.250
Hopefully you've now 
got that figure on screen. 

200
00:11:46.250 --> 00:11:48.374
Let's just think about that figure. 

201
00:11:49.250 --> 00:11:53.500
That's a predicted 
900 million people by 2050 

202
00:11:53.500 --> 00:11:55.797
who could miss out 
on your messages, 

203
00:11:55.797 --> 00:11:58.320
online promotions, 
and offers,

204
00:11:58.320 --> 00:12:01.568
and that's just from people 
who can't access your message 

205
00:12:01.568 --> 00:12:04.000
because they have 
a hearing issue.

206
00:12:04.320 --> 00:12:06.571
On top of that, 
you have all those people 

207
00:12:06.571 --> 00:12:10.000
who can't access the message 
for a variety of other reasons.

208
00:12:13.680 --> 00:12:15.680
Let's have a look at 
some of those reasons.

209
00:12:17.440 --> 00:12:19.000
These are just 
some of the ways 

210
00:12:19.000 --> 00:12:22.963
that subtitling or captions 
can be used 

211
00:12:22.963 --> 00:12:25.000
and are being used.

212
00:12:26.800 --> 00:12:29.194
Subtitles facilitate the translation 

213
00:12:29.194 --> 00:12:33.517
of the original language 
medium into other languages. 

214
00:12:33.517 --> 00:12:36.053
Today, I've provided subtitles 

215
00:12:36.053 --> 00:12:39.990
which are being translated 
into a number of languages 

216
00:12:39.990 --> 00:12:42.990
as part of WordPress 
translation celebrations this week.

217
00:12:44.320 --> 00:12:47.500
To get your talks and videos 
used around the world, 

218
00:12:47.500 --> 00:12:50.548
make sure you add subtitles, 

219
00:12:50.548 --> 00:12:52.895
as it makes it so much easier, 

220
00:12:52.895 --> 00:12:57.871
and in some cases actually 
makes it possible for others

221
00:12:57.871 --> 00:13:01.721
to translate the text 
into their own languages. 

222
00:13:01.721 --> 00:13:06.248
This might be that they translate 
in their heads as they watch along,

223
00:13:06.248 --> 00:13:07.691
or that they use apps 

224
00:13:07.691 --> 00:13:10.840
when they're reviewing 
what you have told them.

225
00:13:13.280 --> 00:13:15.980
For those of us whose 
first language is English, 

226
00:13:15.980 --> 00:13:18.855
it can be hard to comprehend 

227
00:13:18.855 --> 00:13:21.023
how much this translating 
function of subtitles 

228
00:13:21.023 --> 00:13:23.640
matters in everyday life.

229
00:13:23.840 --> 00:13:27.920
Subtitling television programs, 
films, and online video entertainment

230
00:13:27.920 --> 00:13:32.760
is much more common in countries 
where English is not the main language.

231
00:13:33.360 --> 00:13:35.080
The need for these language tools 

232
00:13:35.080 --> 00:13:37.760
to be part of business plans 
and marketing campaigns

233
00:13:38.400 --> 00:13:43.440
is frankly much better understood 
in many of those countries. 

234
00:13:43.440 --> 00:13:45.520
We also need to remember: 

235
00:13:45.520 --> 00:13:49.086
we live in a multicultural 
and multilingual world. 

236
00:13:49.086 --> 00:13:52.686
Your customers and stakeholders 
in your target locations 

237
00:13:52.686 --> 00:13:56.160
are likely to come from 
different language backgrounds

238
00:13:56.800 --> 00:13:59.560
and have varying levels of fluency. 

239
00:14:00.560 --> 00:14:03.380
Trends show that 
the world's increasing appetite 

240
00:14:03.380 --> 00:14:07.478
for online learning 
is matched by its demand 

241
00:14:07.478 --> 00:14:10.920
for being able to access videos 
while on the move.

242
00:14:10.960 --> 00:14:14.399
Train and bus travel 
with improvements in Wi-Fi 

243
00:14:14.399 --> 00:14:18.424
have seen commuter journeys 
turn into mini classrooms for one, 

244
00:14:18.424 --> 00:14:22.960
with noise cancelling headsets 
creating the complete study experience.

245
00:14:24.560 --> 00:14:27.751
In our current times, 
audiences often watch 

246
00:14:27.751 --> 00:14:29.277
– and want to watch – 

247
00:14:29.277 --> 00:14:34.231
video content in busy households, 
particularly during COVID. 

248
00:14:34.231 --> 00:14:38.454
Or in bed, and don't wish 
to disturb other people. 

249
00:14:38.454 --> 00:14:41.725
Much of this learning 
and assimilation 

250
00:14:41.725 --> 00:14:45.976
is only maximized 
through having subtitles. 

251
00:14:45.976 --> 00:14:48.131
They also cut 
through the noise 

252
00:14:48.131 --> 00:14:50.343
that surrounds us 
on public transport, 

253
00:14:50.343 --> 00:14:52.537
shared offices, 
or wherever we choose 

254
00:14:52.537 --> 00:14:55.000
to access the information.

255
00:14:56.320 --> 00:14:58.574
There may be times 
when it's helpful 

256
00:14:58.574 --> 00:15:00.354
to watch a video individually 

257
00:15:00.354 --> 00:15:02.722
or as a group 
without the sound on 

258
00:15:02.722 --> 00:15:04.372
in places where background noise 

259
00:15:04.372 --> 00:15:07.680
may make it impossible 
to have sound at audible levels.

260
00:15:08.960 --> 00:15:11.840
Please think about those occasions 
where you have found that

261
00:15:12.880 --> 00:15:15.609
and how much more 
useful you found it, 

262
00:15:15.609 --> 00:15:17.520
if there had been subtitles.

263
00:15:20.400 --> 00:15:22.789
Many people do not 
have the sound on, 

264
00:15:22.789 --> 00:15:26.586
on their mobile devices 
while traveling or in offices. 

265
00:15:26.586 --> 00:15:29.486
Increasingly, content 
is being accessed, 

266
00:15:29.486 --> 00:15:32.800
videos are being played 
on those mobile devices.

267
00:15:38.160 --> 00:15:40.193
A colleague of mine in 
the subtitling campaign, 

268
00:15:40.193 --> 00:15:42.501
Sean Cunningham, 
Siobhan Cunningham,

269
00:15:42.501 --> 00:15:44.320
from the Yoast Academy's 
e-learning team,

270
00:15:47.040 --> 00:15:50.325
she always explains: 
it is about the word.

271
00:15:50.325 --> 00:15:52.923
If you see someone talk 
you might 

272
00:15:52.923 --> 00:15:55.250
take in some of 
what they're saying, 

273
00:15:55.250 --> 00:15:59.456
but by having subtitles 
and being able to follow the words 

274
00:15:59.456 --> 00:16:03.804
that makes it easier for you 
to follow what they're saying, 

275
00:16:03.804 --> 00:16:06.152
and for your brain to prepa... 

276
00:16:06.152 --> 00:16:08.279
–and you'll have 
to bear with me, 

277
00:16:08.279 --> 00:16:10.487
I'll need to just check.

278
00:16:10.487 --> 00:16:13.720
The lip-reading people asked 
me to pause for a moment.

279
00:16:17.760 --> 00:16:20.240
It makes it easier for 
your brain to process it,

280
00:16:20.240 --> 00:16:23.760
and remember it, and better 
understand what you are learning.

281
00:16:26.400 --> 00:16:28.487
She said that 
if she sees words 

282
00:16:28.487 --> 00:16:32.031
that tell her what the 
person is talking about, 

283
00:16:32.031 --> 00:16:35.467
she's more likely to listen, 
more likely to stay, 

284
00:16:35.467 --> 00:16:37.779
more likely to finish the video. 

285
00:16:37.779 --> 00:16:40.900
We all know. 
We've all seen the statistics 

286
00:16:40.900 --> 00:16:43.311
of how long people stay on video. 

287
00:16:43.311 --> 00:16:46.256
People's attention spans 
can be extended 

288
00:16:46.256 --> 00:16:48.907
if we help them 
through subtitles. 

289
00:16:48.907 --> 00:16:52.601
If we're not in 
quiet environments 

290
00:16:52.601 --> 00:16:55.094
but need to access 
learning material online, 

291
00:16:55.094 --> 00:16:57.724
it may be the only 
time of the day 

292
00:16:57.724 --> 00:16:59.580
that we can spend 
our own development 

293
00:16:59.580 --> 00:17:02.000
or keeping up with training, 
that is now essential 

294
00:17:02.000 --> 00:17:04.046
for our everyday work. 

295
00:17:04.046 --> 00:17:06.982
All those really great 
talks from WordCamps 

296
00:17:06.982 --> 00:17:10.852
that you would like people 
all over the world to access? 

297
00:17:10.852 --> 00:17:14.748
Subtitle them. Someone might 
then be able to access them 

298
00:17:14.748 --> 00:17:16.593
at a time that suits them 

299
00:17:16.593 --> 00:17:20.600
– an environment that 
they are currently in.

300
00:17:27.520 --> 00:17:30.594
From an education
and training perspective,

301
00:17:30.594 --> 00:17:33.167
provision of visual representations 

302
00:17:33.167 --> 00:17:36.018
of technical terms, 
jargon, and acronyms 

303
00:17:36.018 --> 00:17:38.800
allow for the 
reinforcement of learning.

304
00:17:40.080 --> 00:17:43.280
The three key learning styles that 
I'm sure you've heard of elsewhere

305
00:17:43.840 --> 00:17:46.823
are visual, auditory, and kinetic. 

306
00:17:46.823 --> 00:17:50.120
You should hopefully see 
these now on screen.

307
00:17:52.720 --> 00:17:56.764
That basically means that people 
learn visually through seeing, 

308
00:17:56.764 --> 00:17:58.927
auditory through hearing, 

309
00:17:58.927 --> 00:18:02.174
and kinetic through doing. 

310
00:18:02.974 --> 00:18:05.661
All of these styles of learning 
are better supported 

311
00:18:05.661 --> 00:18:09.000
when the visual picture 
and the audio commentary 

312
00:18:09.000 --> 00:18:13.840
is reinforced with a 
visual underscoring of text.

313
00:18:14.640 --> 00:18:18.768
Even without the express 
intention of educating, 

314
00:18:18.768 --> 00:18:22.400
provision of subtitles 
can even subliminally

315
00:18:22.400 --> 00:18:24.824
help speakers of other 
languages acquire 

316
00:18:24.824 --> 00:18:28.840
or appreciate subtleties 
of the original language.

317
00:18:28.840 --> 00:18:32.506
Usage, slang, 
the idiomatic phrases we all use, 

318
00:18:32.506 --> 00:18:35.320
spelling and much more.

319
00:18:38.240 --> 00:18:42.080
The automated transcription 
software service Sonix 

320
00:18:42.080 --> 00:18:45.886
has found that 80 percent 
of all social media videos 

321
00:18:45.886 --> 00:18:48.112
are viewed with the sound off.

322
00:18:48.112 --> 00:18:51.200
A statistic which might 
make you think that

323
00:18:51.200 --> 00:18:55.023
doing that defeats 
the object of the medium. 

324
00:18:55.023 --> 00:18:59.440
Be that as it may, 
it also poses an opportunity

325
00:18:59.440 --> 00:19:03.682
to reach that switch off 
audience more effectively 

326
00:19:03.682 --> 00:19:05.313
by using subtitles. 

327
00:19:05.313 --> 00:19:07.760
Being able to read information

328
00:19:07.760 --> 00:19:11.800
to absorb the content 
helps us to understand,

329
00:19:11.800 --> 00:19:15.840
respond, explore, 
and apply that knowledge.

330
00:19:18.000 --> 00:19:21.386
Subtitles really do reinforce learning. 

331
00:19:21.386 --> 00:19:27.207
I've worked in learning and CPD 
for nearly 20 years or more, 

332
00:19:27.207 --> 00:19:30.756
and every time 
we have subtitles, 

333
00:19:30.756 --> 00:19:34.500
I know the learners 
are learning more.

334
00:19:34.500 --> 00:19:36.894
They're accessing more, 
retaining it more, 

335
00:19:36.894 --> 00:19:38.840
and they're being 
able to apply it.

336
00:19:40.640 --> 00:19:42.536
Subtitling can now be achieved 

337
00:19:42.536 --> 00:19:46.901
increasingly quickly and economically 

338
00:19:46.901 --> 00:19:51.840
through newer technology 
and online tools.

339
00:19:55.840 --> 00:19:57.457
Please try and keep 
that in your minds 

340
00:19:57.457 --> 00:20:03.080
and think about how you would 
want to access content.

341
00:20:05.600 --> 00:20:08.865
People often say, 
"Is a picture worth a thousand words?" 

342
00:20:08.865 --> 00:20:12.999
Well, if you can't hear 
the words of a talking picture 

343
00:20:12.999 --> 00:20:17.080
and then no clues 
of what is being said,

344
00:20:17.360 --> 00:20:20.844
how is that person going to 
take in your messages? 

345
00:20:20.844 --> 00:20:23.720
How are they going to learn?

346
00:20:24.960 --> 00:20:27.440
Do you really want them to 
just be watching paint dry?

347
00:20:28.640 --> 00:20:30.827
For the people in the audience 
who are going to tell me 

348
00:20:30.827 --> 00:20:32.800
that watching paint dry 
is interesting...

349
00:20:33.040 --> 00:20:35.040
then we'll have that discussion 
after the talk.

350
00:20:43.280 --> 00:20:47.936
Search: Search loves subtitles, 

351
00:20:48.000 --> 00:20:53.336
and for a lot of people 
they think, well, why would it? 

352
00:20:53.336 --> 00:20:54.648
Because search is an index video.

353
00:20:54.648 --> 00:21:00.725
Well, Googlebot and other 
spiders which are crawling around 

354
00:21:00.725 --> 00:21:05.289
(I always have to shiver 
when I think about these spiders), 

355
00:21:05.289 --> 00:21:09.560
they're incessantly 
indexing web pages.

356
00:21:10.080 --> 00:21:13.683
They can't watch 
those moving images 

357
00:21:13.683 --> 00:21:15.316
and they can't 
listen to the audio

358
00:21:15.316 --> 00:21:17.512
–not yet, not really– 

359
00:21:17.512 --> 00:21:21.624
but they can hone in 
on captions. 

360
00:21:21.624 --> 00:21:24.200
Videos with closed captions 

361
00:21:24.200 --> 00:21:27.888
rank higher on Google search 
than those without 

362
00:21:27.888 --> 00:21:29.506
according to a 
study carried out 

363
00:21:29.506 --> 00:21:32.600
by US broadcaster 
American Digital Networks.

364
00:21:34.240 --> 00:21:36.735
In addition, 
some advanced searches 

365
00:21:36.735 --> 00:21:40.854
allow for more specific searching 
of closed captions. 

366
00:21:40.854 --> 00:21:42.344
It goes without saying that 

367
00:21:42.344 --> 00:21:44.400
additional traffic directed 
to your site

368
00:21:44.400 --> 00:21:45.975
by a high search ranking, 

369
00:21:45.975 --> 00:21:48.075
will lead to an increase in traffic 

370
00:21:48.075 --> 00:21:49.602
to other landing pages or 

371
00:21:49.602 --> 00:21:52.526
content you want to 
bring to the party. 

372
00:21:52.526 --> 00:21:55.611
The benefits for engagement 
and SEO combined 

373
00:21:55.611 --> 00:21:59.743
make a powerful argument 
for ensuring your online videos 

374
00:21:59.743 --> 00:22:03.440
are posted with accurate, 
legible, closed captions.

375
00:22:04.480 --> 00:22:07.525
Legible I'm gonna 
stop on for a moment. 

376
00:22:07.525 --> 00:22:11.547
Please, if you've not sure 
about how to do legible, 

377
00:22:11.547 --> 00:22:16.881
there have been other talks 
during this accessibility session 

378
00:22:16.881 --> 00:22:19.760
which will explain 
how to do that,

379
00:22:19.760 --> 00:22:23.869
how many words to have 
on screen, the font sizes.

380
00:22:23.869 --> 00:22:25.989
Please, if you're going 
to create captions, 

381
00:22:25.989 --> 00:22:29.757
don't create them so small 
and all jumbled together 

382
00:22:29.757 --> 00:22:31.800
that people can't access them.

383
00:22:33.360 --> 00:22:36.705
The Scottish audience development company 
Culture Republic, 

384
00:22:36.705 --> 00:22:38.240
runs workshops in captioning

385
00:22:38.240 --> 00:22:41.413
and they assert that adding 
captions to YouTube videos 

386
00:22:41.413 --> 00:22:45.600
has shown to increase completed 
viewings by around seven percent. 

387
00:22:45.600 --> 00:22:48.505
That also helps your 
search engines, ratings 

388
00:22:48.505 --> 00:22:50.987
and it helps people 
find your content, 

389
00:22:50.987 --> 00:22:53.596
stay on your content, 
and refer people. 

390
00:22:53.596 --> 00:22:55.457
They also quote the research 

391
00:22:55.457 --> 00:22:58.452
which shows that 85 percent 
of Facebook views 

392
00:22:58.452 --> 00:22:59.950
occur with muted audio. 

393
00:22:59.950 --> 00:23:05.467
Again this backs up the videos, 
the Sonix statistic. 

394
00:23:05.467 --> 00:23:09.811
I will apologize. I'm running 
a temperature at the moment, 

395
00:23:09.811 --> 00:23:11.490
so I'm having a 
little bit of difficulty 

396
00:23:11.490 --> 00:23:14.816
trying to focus on the 
mouse on the screen. 

397
00:23:14.816 --> 00:23:20.200
Apologies if the screens 
aren't changing quick enough.

398
00:23:21.520 --> 00:23:24.411
Basically, captions serve 
as a reminder to the viewer 

399
00:23:24.411 --> 00:23:27.915
that we are now at a segment 
of particular interest 

400
00:23:27.915 --> 00:23:31.560
and to switch full 
attention back to it.

401
00:23:33.040 --> 00:23:37.126
Reinforced messaging through 
the use of captions is so important. 

402
00:23:37.126 --> 00:23:40.684
If the consumer is going to 
behave in a selective manner, 

403
00:23:40.684 --> 00:23:42.800
we need to ensure 
he or she knows 

404
00:23:42.800 --> 00:23:45.040
when to exercise 
that selectiveness.

405
00:23:45.040 --> 00:23:49.132
Captioning allows that 
to happen better. 

406
00:23:51.876 --> 00:23:53.615
We've talked about the bots, 

407
00:23:53.615 --> 00:23:56.119
but just to reinforce it
–search, search, search. 

408
00:23:56.119 --> 00:23:57.599
They don't understand it. 

409
00:23:57.599 --> 00:23:59.900
If they've got no value 
they will move on.

410
00:24:02.800 --> 00:24:06.861
I'm going to take you down 
to what's happening now 

411
00:24:06.861 --> 00:24:09.204
with artificial intelligence. 

412
00:24:09.204 --> 00:24:11.149
As with all things tech-related, 

413
00:24:11.149 --> 00:24:15.040
times move on and processes are 
in a state of constant evolution.

414
00:24:16.080 --> 00:24:20.841
Captioning for the last 10 years or so 
has used differing technologies 

415
00:24:20.841 --> 00:24:24.932
including automated speech 
recognition known as ASR. 

416
00:24:26.000 --> 00:24:28.200
ASR is a predictive tool.

417
00:24:28.200 --> 00:24:30.720
It generates word sequences 
from an audio signal.

418
00:24:31.360 --> 00:24:35.000
The result is not always 
a totally accurate rendition 

419
00:24:35.000 --> 00:24:36.880
of what is being said.

420
00:24:36.880 --> 00:24:38.479
The nature of live streaming, 

421
00:24:38.479 --> 00:24:41.000
especially where 
conversation is interactive,

422
00:24:41.920 --> 00:24:44.113
presents challenges to ASR. 

423
00:24:45.080 --> 00:24:48.645
Not all speakers will be 
clear enough in their delivery. 

424
00:24:48.645 --> 00:24:50.991
Background noises 
in their environment 

425
00:24:50.991 --> 00:24:55.960
can seem like a verbal sound 
to be represented in captions to ASR.

426
00:24:56.160 --> 00:24:59.840
How well has it been taught to 
differentiate between sounds?

427
00:25:01.040 --> 00:25:05.000
If discussions get heated, 
people may speak over each other 

428
00:25:05.000 --> 00:25:08.001
or cut another speaker off abruptly.

429
00:25:08.001 --> 00:25:11.273
Again, resulting in a 
muddled set of captions.

430
00:25:11.273 --> 00:25:14.560
In fact, you don't even 
need that to happen.

431
00:25:14.560 --> 00:25:18.122
You can have lots of different 
voices that are similar 

432
00:25:18.122 --> 00:25:20.840
and ASR may not pick it up.

433
00:25:22.320 --> 00:25:24.362
Strong regional or national accents, 

434
00:25:24.362 --> 00:25:26.069
or varieties of inflection 

435
00:25:26.069 --> 00:25:29.508
from different speakers can 
confuse ASR and result in 

436
00:25:29.508 --> 00:25:31.535
misrepresentation in captioning. 

437
00:25:32.000 --> 00:25:34.700
I'm sure we've all sat 
through presentations, 

438
00:25:34.700 --> 00:25:36.115
even TV programs, 

439
00:25:36.115 --> 00:25:39.028
where the captioning has 
been so obviously incorrect 

440
00:25:39.028 --> 00:25:41.840
it can almost be comical.

441
00:25:42.720 --> 00:25:46.123
Except for those who rely on it. 

442
00:25:46.123 --> 00:25:48.900
For them it really is 
not a laughing matter.

443
00:25:50.800 --> 00:25:52.800
You'll all probably be aware 

444
00:25:52.800 --> 00:25:56.025
of the variety of accuracies 
and inaccuracies 

445
00:25:56.025 --> 00:25:57.892
delivered by today's range 

446
00:25:57.892 --> 00:26:01.144
of streaming platforms 
in terms of captioning. 

447
00:26:01.144 --> 00:26:04.907
The consequences of 
misrepresentation via captioning 

448
00:26:04.907 --> 00:26:06.321
are the same 
as the consequences 

449
00:26:06.321 --> 00:26:10.160
of mistranslating 
between two languages.

450
00:26:10.160 --> 00:26:12.701
To be effective, 
the ASR system, 

451
00:26:12.701 --> 00:26:15.017
like Web Captioner and others, 

452
00:26:15.017 --> 00:26:17.085
needs to have been prepped 

453
00:26:17.085 --> 00:26:21.500
with a wide vocabulary 
and specialist words. 

454
00:26:21.500 --> 00:26:24.800
It can also be taught to learn 
in multiple languages,

455
00:26:25.360 --> 00:26:29.052
and any specialist acronyms, 
jargon, tech terminology, 

456
00:26:29.052 --> 00:26:31.360
and so on which 
it might encounter.

457
00:26:33.360 --> 00:26:34.900
If it doesn't recognize 

458
00:26:34.900 --> 00:26:36.347
the content of the source signal, 

459
00:26:36.347 --> 00:26:40.117
it cannot predict 
the patterns of words. 

460
00:26:40.117 --> 00:26:41.652
You will sometimes see 

461
00:26:41.652 --> 00:26:44.189
a "next best" word 
or phrase appear, 

462
00:26:44.189 --> 00:26:46.929
which of course 
will often make 

463
00:26:46.929 --> 00:26:50.097
a nonsense version 
of the original. 

464
00:26:50.097 --> 00:26:54.475
One of the most 
often questions I get is, 

465
00:26:54.475 --> 00:26:56.961
"I've added AI to my streams. 

466
00:26:56.961 --> 00:26:59.969
I've added an automatic captioner, 

467
00:26:59.969 --> 00:27:01.197
that's all I need to do." 

468
00:27:01.197 --> 00:27:04.873
No. You need to train it. 
You need to help it. 

469
00:27:04.873 --> 00:27:07.266
If it helps, think of it 

470
00:27:07.266 --> 00:27:09.830
as your pet dog. 

471
00:27:09.830 --> 00:27:11.600
If it doesn't know 
what the instruction is,

472
00:27:11.600 --> 00:27:13.855
it won't know what to do. 

473
00:27:13.855 --> 00:27:16.552
If it's never heard 
the word "JavaScript" 

474
00:27:16.552 --> 00:27:19.840
it won't know what to say.

475
00:27:21.040 --> 00:27:23.849
During the past year, 
the huge jump in demand 

476
00:27:23.849 --> 00:27:25.887
for online conferencing streaming 

477
00:27:25.887 --> 00:27:27.401
due to COVID restrictions 

478
00:27:27.401 --> 00:27:29.401
has put a greater demand 

479
00:27:29.401 --> 00:27:31.840
on existing automated 
speech recognition systems.

480
00:27:33.200 --> 00:27:36.097
AI engineers, we've all been working 

481
00:27:36.097 --> 00:27:38.003
as fast as we can 

482
00:27:38.003 --> 00:27:41.114
to try and make things easier, 

483
00:27:41.114 --> 00:27:42.642
to make things available. 

484
00:27:42.642 --> 00:27:46.382
But a plea: help us do so. 

485
00:27:46.500 --> 00:27:48.751
Help us test what is out there. 

486
00:27:49.751 --> 00:27:52.459
Tell us where it doesn't work, 

487
00:27:52.659 --> 00:27:54.080
because then we can change it.

488
00:27:56.400 --> 00:27:59.440
The focus shouldn't just be 
on speeding up the process,

489
00:28:00.240 --> 00:28:02.880
it needs to also be about 
improving accuracy.

490
00:28:05.760 --> 00:28:08.457
FaceBook live has been using AI. 

491
00:28:08.757 --> 00:28:10.594
It's been doing away with 

492
00:28:10.594 --> 00:28:12.131
one third of the components 

493
00:28:12.131 --> 00:28:14.000
of a basic ASR system.

494
00:28:15.280 --> 00:28:18.829
Basically, it's been getting rid 
of the pronunciation lexicon 

495
00:28:18.829 --> 00:28:20.702
and it's training the part 

496
00:28:20.702 --> 00:28:22.886
which identifies the individual 

497
00:28:22.886 --> 00:28:25.002
constituent sounds of a word, 

498
00:28:25.002 --> 00:28:28.068
to directly predict 
the characters of a word. 

499
00:28:28.068 --> 00:28:30.299
A language model then determines 

500
00:28:30.299 --> 00:28:32.800
the interrelationship 
of these words.

501
00:28:33.520 --> 00:28:35.576
So that frequency of 
use and words, 

502
00:28:35.576 --> 00:28:37.577
which are commonly strung together,

503
00:28:37.577 --> 00:28:40.759
becomes what it thinks 
you're going to be saying. 

504
00:28:40.759 --> 00:28:41.901
The slimming down 

505
00:28:41.901 --> 00:28:44.184
and improvement 
of accuracy in ASR 

506
00:28:44.184 --> 00:28:47.849
was achieved through 
using tools like PyTorch, 

507
00:28:47.849 --> 00:28:50.255
which was an open source 
machine learning library 

508
00:28:50.255 --> 00:28:51.960
derived from Torch library. 

509
00:28:51.960 --> 00:28:54.898
Please do have a look at it. 

510
00:28:54.898 --> 00:28:57.840
There are lots and lots of ways 
you can help improve that.

511
00:29:00.960 --> 00:29:05.516
Captions open up even more 
accessibility options.

512
00:29:05.516 --> 00:29:06.854
We've already talked about 

513
00:29:06.854 --> 00:29:09.586
the impact of captions 
for translation. 

514
00:29:09.586 --> 00:29:12.800
Another development brought 
through artificial intelligence

515
00:29:13.360 --> 00:29:15.418
is the visual images being created 

516
00:29:15.418 --> 00:29:19.405
based on the descriptive text 
contained in that caption. 

517
00:29:20.005 --> 00:29:21.210
This is going to be 

518
00:29:21.210 --> 00:29:23.742
our next generation 
of captioning tools. 

519
00:29:23.742 --> 00:29:25.840
It's in its very early stages.

520
00:29:26.960 --> 00:29:29.909
We have AI which can 
produce captions 

521
00:29:29.909 --> 00:29:32.253
from data contained in images, 

522
00:29:32.253 --> 00:29:35.669
but only this week the 
Allen Institute for AI 

523
00:29:35.669 --> 00:29:38.218
announced it had 
developed an AI 

524
00:29:38.218 --> 00:29:39.563
which produces imagery 

525
00:29:39.563 --> 00:29:42.469
created from those text captions. 

526
00:29:42.469 --> 00:29:44.720
The results, for those 
who may not have seen them,

527
00:29:45.680 --> 00:29:47.840
are so far restricted 
from looking like 

528
00:29:47.840 --> 00:29:50.000
Picasso might have 
knocked up in a hurry,

529
00:29:50.560 --> 00:29:53.878
but their principle is that 
they generate an image. 

530
00:29:53.878 --> 00:29:56.320
They allow somebody 
who may not be able

531
00:29:56.320 --> 00:29:57.678
to understand without 

532
00:29:57.678 --> 00:29:59.592
an image added 
to those words 

533
00:29:59.592 --> 00:30:02.000
the full context of 
what is being said.

534
00:30:02.560 --> 00:30:04.950
Or they may not be 
able to process it because 

535
00:30:04.950 --> 00:30:07.840
their neuroprocessing is different.

536
00:30:08.800 --> 00:30:10.267
This is going to take 

537
00:30:10.267 --> 00:30:12.267
what we can do with captions 

538
00:30:12.267 --> 00:30:13.733
to a whole new realm. 

539
00:30:13.733 --> 00:30:15.002
It's going to make 

540
00:30:15.002 --> 00:30:18.593
even more accessible information. 

541
00:30:18.593 --> 00:30:21.926
If you don't have captions, 

542
00:30:21.926 --> 00:30:24.000
if you haven't introduced subtitling

543
00:30:24.000 --> 00:30:26.106
into your business plans already, 

544
00:30:26.106 --> 00:30:28.026
when this technology develops 

545
00:30:28.026 --> 00:30:29.760
you won't be able to use it,

546
00:30:30.400 --> 00:30:32.302
because it relies on having those 

547
00:30:32.302 --> 00:30:35.297
subtitles in the first place. 

548
00:30:35.297 --> 00:30:37.446
Eventually, the work that is 

549
00:30:37.446 --> 00:30:39.739
happening on these developments 

550
00:30:39.739 --> 00:30:42.352
is that the final image 

551
00:30:42.352 --> 00:30:43.872
will be of photographic quality 

552
00:30:43.872 --> 00:30:45.735
with color, scale, and proportion 

553
00:30:45.735 --> 00:30:48.944
all correctly represented. 

554
00:30:48.944 --> 00:30:51.809
When I'm talking 
about an apple 

555
00:30:51.809 --> 00:30:56.273
and how that relates 
to a concept I'm describing, 

556
00:30:56.273 --> 00:30:58.505
that would also appear. 

557
00:30:58.505 --> 00:31:01.541
If I'm talking about 
a flowchart, 

558
00:31:01.541 --> 00:31:04.218
eventually that 
would also appear. 

559
00:31:04.218 --> 00:31:06.908
Again, it requires 
us to help teach it, 

560
00:31:06.908 --> 00:31:08.880
but that is where the 
technology is going.

561
00:31:11.040 --> 00:31:13.693
A simplified explanation 
of that process is that 

562
00:31:13.693 --> 00:31:15.232
a machine learning algorithm 

563
00:31:15.232 --> 00:31:17.186
has been trained to recognize 

564
00:31:17.186 --> 00:31:18.763
conceptual connections 

565
00:31:18.763 --> 00:31:21.093
between language and visual data. 

566
00:31:21.093 --> 00:31:23.663
An illustration of 
this would be that 

567
00:31:23.663 --> 00:31:24.652
given the text 

568
00:31:24.652 --> 00:31:27.255
"a clock tower in the middle of town," 

569
00:31:27.255 --> 00:31:29.070
the technology produces an image 

570
00:31:29.070 --> 00:31:33.212
of a taller tower-like structure 
with a clock at the top 

571
00:31:33.212 --> 00:31:34.880
surrounded by less high buildings.

572
00:31:35.680 --> 00:31:39.028
Suddenly, people are receiving 

573
00:31:39.028 --> 00:31:42.000
the spoken word, 
the written word, 

574
00:31:42.000 --> 00:31:43.680
and a visual representation.

575
00:31:43.680 --> 00:31:45.680
Think how powerful 

576
00:31:45.680 --> 00:31:48.600
that combination is going to be.

577
00:31:51.920 --> 00:31:55.031
We already have tools 
like Web Captioner.

578
00:31:55.031 --> 00:31:56.957
If you are doing an event 

579
00:31:56.957 --> 00:31:59.899
and you don't have resources 

580
00:31:59.699 --> 00:32:02.085
to purchase live captioning 

581
00:32:02.085 --> 00:32:04.800
done by humans, 
which is a preferred option,

582
00:32:06.160 --> 00:32:09.026
please look at tools 
like Web Captioner. 

583
00:32:09.026 --> 00:32:11.939
There are other ones 
on the market, too. 

584
00:32:11.939 --> 00:32:13.613
They use Google APIs 

585
00:32:13.613 --> 00:32:16.163
generated to create captions, 

586
00:32:16.163 --> 00:32:18.891
but invest the time. 

587
00:32:18.891 --> 00:32:21.120
Invest the time in 
actually training it.

588
00:32:22.080 --> 00:32:24.599
We tested this in a 
number of WordCamps 

589
00:32:24.599 --> 00:32:26.992
including WordCamp Dublin last year, 

590
00:32:26.992 --> 00:32:29.346
and we asked all speakers 

591
00:32:29.346 --> 00:32:32.235
to practice saying a 
couple of sentences 

592
00:32:32.235 --> 00:32:36.173
from their talk into 
Web Captioner. 

593
00:32:36.173 --> 00:32:39.455
Picking the right option 

594
00:32:39.455 --> 00:32:44.540
that successfully produced 
the text that they were saying.

595
00:32:44.720 --> 00:32:47.393
We also asked them 
to tell us the words 

596
00:32:47.393 --> 00:32:50.800
and the jargon that would 
not be necessarily known

597
00:32:50.800 --> 00:32:52.817
or that may, 
with a strong accent, 

598
00:32:52.817 --> 00:32:54.738
sound slightly different 

599
00:32:54.738 --> 00:32:57.964
to what Web Captioner 
had learnt already. 

600
00:32:57.964 --> 00:33:01.267
We inputted that text 
into Web Captioner, 

601
00:33:01.267 --> 00:33:05.195
and it was wonderful to see 
that in most cases, 

602
00:33:05.195 --> 00:33:08.730
that improved the captions 
that we produced 

603
00:33:08.730 --> 00:33:10.987
to a 98% level. 

604
00:33:10.987 --> 00:33:12.526
It didn't get everything. 

605
00:33:12.526 --> 00:33:14.723
It still had issues. 

606
00:33:14.723 --> 00:33:18.985
"Huddersfield" is always 
going to be heard wrong. 

607
00:33:18.985 --> 00:33:21.850
It's just one of those 
words that captioners, 

608
00:33:21.850 --> 00:33:24.986
an auto captioner, 
does not get right, 

609
00:33:24.986 --> 00:33:28.038
but it's a huge step forward. 

610
00:33:28.038 --> 00:33:29.975
Since WordCamp Dublin, 

611
00:33:29.975 --> 00:33:31.744
there has been much 
more developments 

612
00:33:31.744 --> 00:33:33.780
and tests in tools like this.

613
00:33:34.000 --> 00:33:37.426
Web Captioner has, 
in the last few weeks, 

614
00:33:37.426 --> 00:33:41.076
released a beta version 
which you can test, 

615
00:33:41.076 --> 00:33:44.548
and you can add 
to things like Zoom, 

616
00:33:44.548 --> 00:33:47.189
to other video conferencing materials. 

617
00:33:47.189 --> 00:33:48.560
We're currently doing tests on this

618
00:33:48.560 --> 00:33:52.070
in the WordPress Marketing 
and WordPress TV teams 

619
00:33:52.070 --> 00:33:55.440
as well as tests with 
other facilities like AWS,

620
00:33:55.440 --> 00:33:57.976
and how we can use 
auto-generated captions 

621
00:33:57.976 --> 00:34:00.705
from those facilities 

622
00:34:00.705 --> 00:34:03.609
to then correct 
and start subtitling 

623
00:34:03.609 --> 00:34:05.291
more and more videos, 

624
00:34:05.291 --> 00:34:07.268
and with your help 

625
00:34:07.268 --> 00:34:09.400
making that possible.

626
00:34:10.160 --> 00:34:14.384
OBS, which is a 
open source software 

627
00:34:14.384 --> 00:34:18.100
also now has a 
beta version of captioning. 

628
00:34:18.100 --> 00:34:20.207
If you are doing a talk 

629
00:34:20.207 --> 00:34:23.747
and you're going through 
OBS software for that talk, 

630
00:34:23.747 --> 00:34:25.516
and connecting that to Zoom, 

631
00:34:25.516 --> 00:34:27.879
StreamYard, whatever you're using. 

632
00:34:27.879 --> 00:34:31.904
There is a beta version 
that you can now enable 

633
00:34:31.904 --> 00:34:35.603
and that live auto captioning can appear. 

634
00:34:35.603 --> 00:34:40.660
The more people use it, 
the more it will improve, 

635
00:34:40.660 --> 00:34:43.760
but we need people 
to use it, test it, 

636
00:34:43.760 --> 00:34:46.576
to give feedback, 
correct it. 

637
00:34:46.576 --> 00:34:48.073
We need more 
accents to do it, 

638
00:34:48.073 --> 00:34:51.836
we need people with more 
accessibility issues, 

639
00:34:51.836 --> 00:34:55.273
to actually try the software. 

640
00:34:55.273 --> 00:34:57.167
In my work, we have 
a number of people 

641
00:34:57.167 --> 00:34:59.588
who have hearing difficulties 

642
00:34:59.588 --> 00:35:01.840
who are actually now testing 
some of this software.

643
00:35:04.400 --> 00:35:09.398
I focused this talk on the 
why part of captioning.

644
00:35:09.398 --> 00:35:12.160
If you've been convinced
–and I hope you have–

645
00:35:12.160 --> 00:35:14.753
that this is something 
you really should be doing,

646
00:35:14.753 --> 00:35:17.250
I suggest you look at 
the presentation slides

647
00:35:17.250 --> 00:35:19.007
from yesterday's speaker, 
Meryl Evans, 

648
00:35:19.007 --> 00:35:21.880
who's given a handy list 
of tools which you can use.

649
00:35:26.000 --> 00:35:28.432
People don't like being in the dark. 

650
00:35:28.432 --> 00:35:29.840
Help put the light on.

651
00:35:31.120 --> 00:35:34.940
You can also do that, 
and make a difference 

652
00:35:34.940 --> 00:35:37.912
by becoming a subtitling champion. 

653
00:35:37.912 --> 00:35:39.440
It really is easy.

654
00:35:40.160 --> 00:35:43.087
I will guarantee 
you will learn a new skill, 

655
00:35:43.087 --> 00:35:45.760
and we will help you 
learn that new skill.

656
00:35:48.320 --> 00:35:51.120
You can also play a part 
in knowledge sharing,

657
00:35:51.760 --> 00:35:53.477
and the skills that you learn, 

658
00:35:53.477 --> 00:35:54.852
and the knowledge that you share, 

659
00:35:54.852 --> 00:35:58.136
is much wider than the 
WordPress environment, 

660
00:35:58.136 --> 00:35:59.885
the open source environment. 

661
00:35:59.885 --> 00:36:02.584
It can make a difference 
in your products, 

662
00:36:02.584 --> 00:36:04.342
your company, your culture. 

663
00:36:04.342 --> 00:36:05.974
It can make a difference 

664
00:36:05.974 --> 00:36:07.920
in how we deal with information

665
00:36:08.880 --> 00:36:11.234
and people's access to it. 

666
00:36:12.034 --> 00:36:14.304
Please invest in subtitling. 

667
00:36:14.304 --> 00:36:16.000
Please don't put up 

668
00:36:16.000 --> 00:36:18.758
half thought about solutions. 

669
00:36:18.758 --> 00:36:21.447
Work out how it's going to work. 

670
00:36:21.447 --> 00:36:24.560
For a lot of the camps, 
today's event too,

671
00:36:24.560 --> 00:36:28.824
they also have another option 
where you can read subtitles 

672
00:36:28.824 --> 00:36:30.560
that can be changed 
into different fonts.

673
00:36:31.840 --> 00:36:34.121
YouTube subtitling for live feed 

674
00:36:34.121 --> 00:36:36.067
is really difficult to read. 

675
00:36:36.067 --> 00:36:38.273
It's very difficult to process 

676
00:36:38.273 --> 00:36:41.513
if you have any kind of 
neuroprocessing issue. 

677
00:36:41.513 --> 00:36:44.960
It can be very difficult 
if you just wear glasses.

678
00:36:48.320 --> 00:36:52.483
Support the WP diversity 
and tech accessibility. 

679
00:36:52.483 --> 00:36:55.064
It will give you huge rewards, 

680
00:36:55.064 --> 00:36:57.347
but it also means that the people 

681
00:36:57.347 --> 00:36:59.370
who really need the technology 

682
00:36:59.370 --> 00:37:02.316
don't have to be making 
that call themselves 

683
00:37:02.316 --> 00:37:04.213
all the time. 

684
00:37:04.213 --> 00:37:07.535
This should be something 
that we do from scratch, 

685
00:37:07.535 --> 00:37:09.880
that we include in 
all our planning.

686
00:37:12.320 --> 00:37:14.031
Finally, tell your speakers 

687
00:37:14.031 --> 00:37:15.920
when you're planning a WordCamp,

688
00:37:15.920 --> 00:37:18.904
or any kind of online event, 

689
00:37:18.904 --> 00:37:21.840
or even in-person event 
when we're allowed to again.

690
00:37:23.680 --> 00:37:27.427
Help them understand 
about providing text 

691
00:37:27.427 --> 00:37:28.903
even after the event 

692
00:37:28.903 --> 00:37:31.080
so subtitles can be done quicker.

693
00:37:32.240 --> 00:37:34.088
Help them even commit 

694
00:37:34.088 --> 00:37:37.365
to subtitling something of their own. 

695
00:37:37.365 --> 00:37:40.150
With the auto captioning 
tools that now exist 

696
00:37:40.150 --> 00:37:43.728
it doesn't have to take 
a huge amount of time. 

697
00:37:43.728 --> 00:37:46.267
Sometimes, where it takes time 

698
00:37:46.267 --> 00:37:48.578
is because of unfamiliarity with 

699
00:37:48.578 --> 00:37:49.837
where the speaker's going, 

700
00:37:49.837 --> 00:37:51.281
what they're talking about, 

701
00:37:51.281 --> 00:37:52.840
and the jargon.

702
00:37:55.120 --> 00:37:57.257
Please come and join our campaign. 

703
00:37:57.257 --> 00:37:59.760
You can make a difference 
for inclusion,

704
00:37:59.760 --> 00:38:02.799
diversity, and user experience. 

705
00:38:02.799 --> 00:38:05.920
It will improve your organization's 
messaging and reach.

706
00:38:07.680 --> 00:38:11.360
It will make it different. 
It may even help you one day.

707
00:38:12.720 --> 00:38:13.843
Thank you. 

708
00:38:13.843 --> 00:38:18.541
You can find me on 
@NonStopNewsUK on Twitter. 

709
00:38:18.541 --> 00:38:22.692
If anyone, I know I have 
had a lot of questions 

710
00:38:22.692 --> 00:38:25.909
that have come in on 
Twitter as well already, 

711
00:38:25.909 --> 00:38:28.114
I will make sure I answer 
those in the next few days. 

712
00:38:29.114 --> 00:38:31.577
I had a request for 
a couple of people 

713
00:38:31.577 --> 00:38:33.022
who'd like to do an 
interactive session 

714
00:38:33.022 --> 00:38:34.755
learning how to use Amara 

715
00:38:34.755 --> 00:38:37.097
and we have got 
those planned, too. 

716
00:38:37.097 --> 00:38:41.022
Please do contact me on Twitter 
on @NonStopNewsUK, 

717
00:38:41.022 --> 00:38:44.331
on Slack on @abhanonstopnewsuk 

718
00:38:44.331 --> 00:38:46.640
and we will connect you 
with those things.

719
00:38:49.120 --> 00:38:53.550
<v Amanda Bailey> Thank you so much Abha. 
That was wonderful. 

720
00:38:53.550 --> 00:38:55.852
I'm so full of information. 

721
00:38:55.852 --> 00:38:58.383
We really appreciate you 
sharing your expertise 

722
00:38:58.383 --> 00:39:01.349
and breaking down the kinds 
of captions and subtitles, 

723
00:39:01.349 --> 00:39:02.877
how essential they are to learning. 

724
00:39:02.877 --> 00:39:07.781
There was a lot of conversation 
in the YouTube stream chat too, 

725
00:39:07.781 --> 00:39:09.145
and we do have some questions, 

726
00:39:09.145 --> 00:39:14.429
that we have a little less 
than 10 minutes to get to.

727
00:39:14.429 --> 00:39:17.318
If you don't mind [laughs],

728
00:39:17.318 --> 00:39:20.043
the first question 
that I'm going to ask, 

729
00:39:20.043 --> 00:39:23.763
I think the first question was 
mostly answered in the chat, 

730
00:39:23.763 --> 00:39:26.006
but their comment was: 

731
00:39:26.006 --> 00:39:28.820
"It's very interesting about 
non-English speaking countries 

732
00:39:28.820 --> 00:39:31.280
having adopted captions 
at a greater rate.

733
00:39:32.160 --> 00:39:33.800
Which countries do you feel 

734
00:39:33.800 --> 00:39:37.818
set the standard in terms of subtitles?" 

735
00:39:37.818 --> 00:39:43.041
<v Abha> The Spanish film industry has 
actually been really good at this, 

736
00:39:43.041 --> 00:39:47.253
and there has been some 
working with the US as well, 

737
00:39:47.253 --> 00:39:50.124
which is, it's been 
very good in terms of 

738
00:39:50.124 --> 00:39:51.600
how subtitles are presented.

739
00:39:52.400 --> 00:39:56.896
I think that has been a 
model that lots of other 

740
00:39:56.896 --> 00:39:58.400
smaller broadcasting 
things have taken on.

741
00:39:59.840 --> 00:40:03.814
In terms of actual conferencing, 

742
00:40:03.814 --> 00:40:09.455
where countries have a 
regulatory requirement to caption, 

743
00:40:09.455 --> 00:40:13.622
it is worth having a look at 
the processes that they use, 

744
00:40:13.622 --> 00:40:16.784
because they tend 
to be more tested, 

745
00:40:16.784 --> 00:40:19.913
and they have tended to 
look at the various options 

746
00:40:19.913 --> 00:40:22.939
and how they can do that. 

747
00:40:22.939 --> 00:40:26.883
America has had a lot 
of regulation on that. 

748
00:40:26.883 --> 00:40:29.527
Some of the big charities have 
also done some work on that 

749
00:40:29.527 --> 00:40:33.684
and I can share some links 
after this talk, as well. 

750
00:40:34.144 --> 00:40:35.654
<v Amanda> Perfect, thank you.

751
00:40:36.554 --> 00:40:37.706
The next question is: 

752
00:40:37.706 --> 00:40:40.725
"SEO and YouTube are hidden gems 

753
00:40:40.725 --> 00:40:44.604
for building our online footprint, 
as you mentioned.

754
00:40:44.604 --> 00:40:49.990
Are there rules for effective content 

755
00:40:49.990 --> 00:40:53.256
for web pages, links, 
etc., for captioning, 

756
00:40:53.256 --> 00:40:58.316
to help videos rank higher, 
or rank more?" 

757
00:40:58.316 --> 00:41:01.100
<v Abha> There's a lot of work 
going on at the moment 

758
00:41:01.100 --> 00:41:03.951
in terms of readability of captions, 

759
00:41:03.951 --> 00:41:06.429
and there's some work 
that's been pioneering 

760
00:41:06.429 --> 00:41:10.919
in Switzerland about how algorithms 

761
00:41:10.919 --> 00:41:13.840
can give a higher rating 
to captions that are readable.

762
00:41:15.480 --> 00:41:17.421
Captions that come in 
huge blocks of text 

763
00:41:17.421 --> 00:41:20.027
with no punctuation, 

764
00:41:20.027 --> 00:41:25.433
would have a lower reach. 

765
00:41:25.433 --> 00:41:27.477
There are some testing 
that's going on 

766
00:41:27.477 --> 00:41:28.960
with a couple of 
the big providers,

767
00:41:28.960 --> 00:41:33.488
for how that can 
be more promoted. 

768
00:41:33.488 --> 00:41:36.400
You'll notice that some
automatic translation things

769
00:41:36.400 --> 00:41:40.533
particularly YouTube, 
misses out punctuation. 

770
00:41:40.533 --> 00:41:43.280
When people are then 
watching the video back,

771
00:41:43.280 --> 00:41:47.417
actually the bots are not 
understanding what's being said, 

772
00:41:47.417 --> 00:41:49.969
because there's no 
punctuation to help them. 

773
00:41:49.969 --> 00:41:51.065
So if you put punctuation in,

774
00:41:51.065 --> 00:41:54.000
that does increase the 
searchability of that, 

775
00:41:54.000 --> 00:41:55.920
and the ranking.

776
00:41:56.320 --> 00:41:59.128
<v Amanda> Great, that's helpful to know. 

777
00:41:59.128 --> 00:42:02.560
