00:42:06.776 --> 00:42:08.971
The next question 
for you, Abha, is: 

781
00:42:08.971 --> 00:42:11.321
"What is your opinion in delaying audio 

782
00:42:11.321 --> 00:42:13.156
and video signal at live events 

783
00:42:13.156 --> 00:42:17.417
in order to give more time to 
live transcribers or AI tools 

784
00:42:17.417 --> 00:42:20.560
to be correct with the 
subtitles or captions,

785
00:42:20.560 --> 00:42:23.798
and deliver them synchronized?" 

786
00:42:25.260 --> 00:42:27.319
<v Abha> It's a really big problem. 

787
00:42:27.319 --> 00:42:28.665
Just looking at today's, 

788
00:42:28.665 --> 00:42:30.790
I know my screen over here, 
which has been live, 

789
00:42:30.790 --> 00:42:33.520
has been quite behind 
what I've been doing.

790
00:42:33.520 --> 00:42:37.531
A lot of the software like OBS 
has a real issue with this, 

791
00:42:37.531 --> 00:42:40.440
because it creates a 
delay between video 

792
00:42:40.440 --> 00:42:42.693
and what you're actually saying, 

793
00:42:42.693 --> 00:42:45.726
which causes a difficulty for 
anybody who's lip-reading, 

794
00:42:45.726 --> 00:42:47.596
because they're lip-reading something 

795
00:42:47.596 --> 00:42:50.976
that is then out of context 
with what's behind them, 

796
00:42:50.976 --> 00:42:53.885
or what you're actually 
trying to emphasize, 

797
00:42:53.885 --> 00:42:56.843
so they could see an 
emphasis on something 

798
00:42:56.843 --> 00:43:01.124
that is actually no longer 
being talked about. 

799
00:43:01.124 --> 00:43:04.185
I think that as events, 
and as we become 

800
00:43:04.185 --> 00:43:05.392
more online events, 

801
00:43:05.392 --> 00:43:07.680
we need to think about 
putting a delay in.

802
00:43:07.680 --> 00:43:11.116
We also need to do 
some simpler things, 

803
00:43:11.116 --> 00:43:14.720
like encouraging 
text to be available.

804
00:43:15.520 --> 00:43:18.414
The captioners will 
work a lot quicker 

805
00:43:18.414 --> 00:43:20.080
if they know what jargon 
is going to be used.

806
00:43:20.960 --> 00:43:22.596
So WordCamp London, 

807
00:43:22.596 --> 00:43:26.274
our live captioners 
are very accurate. 

808
00:43:26.274 --> 00:43:29.449
One of the reasons 
for that accuracy 

809
00:43:29.449 --> 00:43:32.783
is because they have the 
jargon and the terminology.

810
00:43:32.783 --> 00:43:36.625
It's quite often the talk words 
from similar speakers, 

811
00:43:36.625 --> 00:43:39.472
and that means that 
they don't have to build in 

812
00:43:39.472 --> 00:43:41.700
that extra delay for everything 
to catch up again. 

813
00:43:41.700 --> 00:43:44.498
It still doesn't avoid 
the internet delay 

814
00:43:44.498 --> 00:43:46.515
that you will have with video, 

815
00:43:46.515 --> 00:43:49.681
but there are easy fixes 
most of the software, 

816
00:43:49.681 --> 00:43:52.056
particularly the paid-for software, 

817
00:43:52.056 --> 00:43:56.088
does actually allow you to 
compensate for that delay. 

818
00:43:56.088 --> 00:43:59.680
There is an expectation now that,

819
00:44:00.240 --> 00:44:02.199
particularly in the commercial world, 

820
00:44:02.199 --> 00:44:04.880
and maybe it needs to come 
to the open source too,

821
00:44:04.880 --> 00:44:06.731
is that if you're 
putting on an event, 

822
00:44:06.731 --> 00:44:08.720
help train your speakers 
in how to do that.

823
00:44:09.600 --> 00:44:11.814
Otherwise, you will have 
people who are, 

824
00:44:11.814 --> 00:44:13.585
regardless of what you do 

825
00:44:13.585 --> 00:44:16.447
in regards to the delay 
that you put in, 

826
00:44:16.447 --> 00:44:18.968
their camera may 
still be adding in 

827
00:44:18.968 --> 00:44:21.840
several seconds of 
the delay in addition.

828
00:44:22.960 --> 00:44:26.240
<v Amanda> Right. 
Thank you for that response.
